data.name: label6.Text
data.value: Once you've got your video recording and Timestamps, go to the Main tab and enter in the paths for each into the tool. Options and Actions for cutting should now appear. In here, you will find options to set up how the tool will read the Timestamp file and do the trimming. You will need to fill these in order to render the video. These include:

data.name: label3.Text
data.value:
Before you use this tool, you will need to download FFmpeg and FFprobe, which are used to do media inspection and video cutting. Links to these can be found in the Dependencies tab.
After that, grab an ASL file corresponding with the engine / game that you're running in the ASL folder beside the tool's .exe file. You can install this by going into your Livesplit's Layout Editor, then adding a Scriptable Auto Splitter by - Right clicking Livesplit > Edit Layout - Clicking the plus icon on the left, then hovering over Control, and select Scriptable Auto Splitter - Double clicking the newly-added Scriptable Auto Splitter entry in the list - Clicking browse, then browse to the aforementioned ASL file. This file is used for detecting and writing the time of loads for cutting.

data.name: label4.Text
data.value:
Now you are ready to record your run! It's recommended you keep Livesplit and the RTA timer visible at all times for figuring out stuff later.
Once you have finished recording your run, you will need to get the Timestamp file for your run that the ASL file generated. This will vary between ASLs made for different games / engines; for Source Engine's ASL, files are stored in the "loading-b-gone_timestamps folder" folder next to Livesplit's .exe.

data.name: label10.Text
data.value:
Load offsets contain values which modify when a load begins and ends, which will change how the tool will trim the video. This is used to adjust Loads if the ASL didn't produce accurate-enough Timestamps
Here is a visualization of a single 1-second load splitting a video segment. Use the sliders on the left to see how modifying the offsets modify the Load. The tool will cut out this Load in the finished video.

data.name: label25.Text
data.value:
Once you've configured everything, you can head down to the Actions section to begin cutting the video. Each button, when pressed, will show a Save File Dialog where you will need to type in the file name of the output file, including an extension. Note that this extension can be whatever FFmpeg can output.
Note that a render will take a while to create, as FFmpeg has to re-encode your video. As such, it is highly recommended you do a preview render first, which will remove a number of loads from the video (customizable in the Settings tab), and will compile them into a short previeo render, where 1 second before and after a load is shown. Each of these previews are separated by a black screen.
